item.title: Runtime Memory Botting
item.dc:creator: @Nerice Nerice
item.description:
@Nerice wrote:

Krichevskoy:

Pity though, most probably lose the idea after you mention abstract classes, and definitely when you mention PUTFIELD and PUTSTATIC.

Some of us do, too bad I missed what was there before he edited it out.

Small example method to grab a few field names to spit out their obbed names… of course when I am grabbing them I am using nothing like this method but it serves its purpose if someone that dont know wants to play around and figure stuff out, as I couldnt find any examples. Its pretty basic, no code constraint used, hardcoded instruction list to look for etc…

private void getSomeFields(MethodGen mg) { InstructionList il = mg.getInstructionList(); String iPat = "getfield iconst_1 if_icmpne aload_0 getfield iconst_2 if_icmpge new dup aload_0 getfield"; //^^spellSelected ^^menuActionRow ^^spellToolTip InstructionFinder f = new InstructionFinder(il); Iterator it = f.search(iPat); if(it.hasNext()) { InstructionHandle[] match = (InstructionHandle[])it.next(); FieldInstruction fi = (FieldInstruction) match[0].getInstruction(); System.out.println("spellSelected is " + fi.getFieldName(mg.getConstantPool())); fi = (FieldInstruction) match[4].getInstruction(); System.out.println("menuActionRow is " + fi.getFieldName(mg.getConstantPool())); fi = (FieldInstruction) match[match.length - 1].getInstruction(); System.out.println("spellTooltip is " + fi.getFieldName(mg.getConstantPool())); } }

I dont even actually use this search pattern (but is a working pattern for these 3 variables, tested against 20 jars), as the one I use to get these 3 fields also gets another 3 fields, a class and 2 methods all at the same time.

Also a question, as far as detectablility, how much does changing the client classes affect that. Like would it be better to update the bot to the client (and also changing the client as little as possible by rerouting methodcalls ie getDocumentBase (instead of rewriting/replacing what they have in thier method), to my own class methods to deal with them without extending the client etc…), or does it matter at all?
